   =20
 =20

The basic analysis of banking is:
=09A bank owns a pile of assets:=C2=A0loans, bonds, etc. Say they are worth=
 $100 today.=09The bank is funded mostly by senior claims on those assets: =
bank deposits and other forms of debt that really should get paid back.=C2=
=A0Say the bank has $90 of debt outstanding against its $100 of assets.=09T=
he bank also has a little sliver of equity: its shareholders have the resid=
ual claim on those assets, after the senior claims=C2=A0paid back. Here the=
 bank has $10 of equity; depositors and other creditors are entitled to the=
 first $90 of the bank=E2=80=99s assets, but anything left over =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0currently $10 =E2=80=94=C2=A0goes to the shareholders.=09The sharehol=
ders, therefore, have a close-to-the-money call option=C2=A0on the bank=E2=
=80=99s assets: If the assets turn out to be worth more than $90, the share=
holders get the excess, but if they turn out to be worth less than $90, the=
 shareholders get nothing. In particular, if the assets turn out to be wort=
h zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0if all $100 of assets turn out to be fake and the ban=
k is worthless =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the shareholders only lose their $10; th=
e other $90 of the losses fall on the depositors. (Or=C2=A0the deposit insu=
rance fund, the taxpayers,=C2=A0etc.)=09This option is more valuable if vol=
atility is higher. If the bank=E2=80=99s assets have a 50/50 chance of endi=
ng up worth $98 or $102, then the shareholders will get back either $8 or $=
12 after paying off the debt, for an expected value of $10. (And the deposi=
tors will always get back their $90.) If the bank=E2=80=99s assets have a 5=
0/50 chance of ending up worth $70 or $130, then the shareholders will get =
back either $0 or $40, for an expected value of $20. And the depositors wil=
l get back $90 in the good case, but only $70 =E2=80=94=C2=A0a catastrophe,=
 a bank failure =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the bad case.=09The bank=E2=80=99s execut=
ives have fiduciary duties to shareholders, and probably own a lot of stock=
 themselves, so they want to make the stock more valuable.=09Again, the the=
oretically correct way to=C2=A0make the stock more valuable is to make the =
assets more volatile, to make the bank riskier, to increase the value of th=
e shareholders=E2=80=99 option.=09Everything else about banks =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0bank regulation, prudential supervision, capital and liquidity requireme=
nts, deposit insurance, rules about bonuses and clawbacks, bank culture and=
 training, speeches by politicians, depictions of banks in popular culture =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is about mitigating this essential problem. The essential pr=
oblem is that, if you look at a bank=E2=80=99s capital structure with some =
financial sophistication but also some naivety, you will say =E2=80=9Cwait =
the bank works for the shareholders, the shareholders have an at-the-money =
option on the assets, and the way to increase shareholder value is to incre=
ase the volatility of those assets.=E2=80=9D

Many stories about banks are that story, the story of someone looking at a =
bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet with financial sophistication and also naivety=
 and saying =E2=80=9Chey what about some more risk?=E2=80=9D Here=E2=80=99s=
 a great one from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Todd Gillespie:

A cadre of McKinsey & Co. consultants strode into a meeting with Houston=E2=
=80=99s most prominent local bank to dwell on the problem bedeviling thousa=
nds of regional banks: How to stay relevant.
=E2=80=9CThe thing that I laugh at, though, is they had a chart,=E2=80=9D s=
aid Steve Stephens, the CEO of Amegy Bank, recalling the presentation to th=
e board of its parent company in late 2022. McKinsey=E2=80=99s message was =
that banks such as Amegy could find a lucrative business niche, like the so=
-called specialty regional banks that it spotlighted in slides, he said.
=E2=80=9CWell, that was First Republic, Silicon Valley Bank and Signature,=
=E2=80=9D said Stephens, all of which collapsed last year. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s specialization that got them.=E2=80=9D

This was good advice, that McKinsey gave him!
  [4]
=C2=A0Find a niche, specialize, make a big bet: Diversification makes you s=
afer but reduces the variance of your returns; specialization increases the=
 variance and thus the likelihood of making a lot of money for shareholders=
. Also the likelihood of going to zero.

