adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Super users</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I think about from time to time=
 is=C2=A0that the notion of =E2=80=9Cmaterial nonpublic information=E2=80=
=9D is outdated and incoherent. In the olden days, you could have some simp=
le intuitions about what constituted insider trading. Some news would obvio=
usly be material to a company=E2=80=99s stock price: If you knew that the c=
ompany was about to announce a merger, or earnings that were much higher th=
an analysts=E2=80=99 expectations, then you could expect that the stock wou=
ld trade up a lot. So you could=C2=A0buy the stock before the announcement,=
 wait a few days, and then sell the stock at a big profit right after the a=
nnouncement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Insider trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0trading on this=
 sort of material nonpublic information =E2=80=94=C2=A0is generally illegal=
, and regulators policed it in intuitive ways: They=C2=A0look at stocks tha=
t move a lot on earnings or merger announcements and see if there=E2=80=99s=
 any suspicious trading by anyone who might have inside information.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile investors were regularly meeting wit=
h corporate managers and talking about their business. Of course they were!=
 The investors wanted to make informed investment decisions, and the manage=
rs had a fiduciary duty to their shareholders to help them understand the b=
usiness. It was good for the companies, and for the investors, to have thes=
e meetings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the managers were <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3=
LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0My4xMDA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd7ebc3=
25" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">not supposed to give the investors</a> any material nonpublic =
information in these meetings. You couldn=E2=80=99t have an investor meetin=
g and say, like, =E2=80=9Cgood news, we=E2=80=99re in talks to be acquired =
by Alphabet next week.=E2=80=9D You couldn=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Cgood news=
, we=E2=80=99re going to announce blowout earnings next week.=E2=80=9D But =
the investors could try to get a more nuanced and detailed understanding of=
 the public information; they could ask questions to sharpen their models a=
nd their sense of=C2=A0how the company made money. The managers could give =
the investors =E2=80=9Ccolor,=E2=80=9D people used to say. Sometimes this w=
as called the =E2=80=9C mosaic theory=E2=80=9D: Management couldn=E2=80=99t=
 just hand the investors big material news, but they could give the investo=
rs little pieces of information, and the investors could combine those piec=
es with other bits of information (public data, what they heard from other =
companies, etc.) to make informed investment decisions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This whole structure rested on the idea that s=
ome information is =E2=80=9Cmaterial=E2=80=9D and therefore has to be discl=
osed to everyone equally, while other information is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em=
>material and yet=C2=A0<em>sophisticated investors want to know it</em>. Th=
at makes some crude intuitive sense: Merger news that will move the stock b=
y 20% is material; nuanced news about earnings line items that will move th=
e stock by 0.5% is not. News that would cause any retail investor to say =
=E2=80=9Coh boy I=E2=80=99d better buy that stock=E2=80=9D is material; new=
s that only a sophisticated expert analyst would find interesting is not.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that divide seems unstable right now. For =
one thing, prosecutors and judges seem skeptical. Here is a <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud=
HVja2VyZWxsaXMuY29tL2xpbmd1YS1uZWdvdGktYmxvZy9pcy10aGUtbW9zYWljLXRoZW9yeS1h=
cy1hLWRlZmVuc2UtdG8taW5zaWRlci10cmFkaW5nLWRlYWQv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc=
586849c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">2018 law firm memo</a> asking =E2=80=9CIs the mosaic theor=
y as a defense to insider trading dead,=E2=80=9D and I occasionally <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDEtMDgvd2hhdC1kby1pbnZl=
c3RvcnMtYW5kLWNvbXBhbmllcy10YWxrLWFib3V0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZ=
GJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQxMC=
Z1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9a767652" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>quote</a> the time US Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor told a lawyer =
that there are =E2=80=9Cregulations to stop=E2=80=9D companies =E2=80=9Ctal=
king to analysts.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But for another thing, modern markets really a=
re more professional and efficient and competitive than they used to be, an=
d the bar for what is material=C2=A0<em>to investors=C2=A0</em>probably is =
lower. If you are an analyst at a hedge fund, and you spend all your time t=
hinking about a couple of dozen companies, and you buy lots of alternative =
data and talk to lots of experts and do lots of investigating of those comp=
anies, and you generally wring every possible insight out of public informa=
tion to inform your trading decisions, well, analysts at a dozen other hedg=
e funds are doing the same thing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And if somebody at a company came to you and s=
aid =E2=80=9Chey here=E2=80=99s a little piece of news that will move our s=
tock by 0.5% next week,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s huge! Your portfolio manage=
r runs=C2=A0a highly levered, factor-neutral, short-term investing strategy=
; if you can regularly bring her 0.5% idiosyncratic weekly profits, that tr=
anslates into vast riches for all of you. Algorithmic trading firms mint bi=
llionaires by being right 51% of the time; a little bit of reliable edge, i=
n modern markets, is=C2=A0hugely valuable. It makes no sense to say that it=
=E2=80=99s not material.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I talk a lot about stocks, but this is true ev=
erywhere. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34992=
007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQt=
MDItMjkvdGhlLWJvYXJkLW9mLWRpcmVjdG9ycy1pcy1pbi1jaGFyZ2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxMDI=
0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3=
Rlcm09MjQwNDEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB876=
9fe79" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">talked a few weeks ago</a> about a weird email from the US L=
abor Department=E2=80=99s Bureau of Labor Statistics to a list of =E2=80=9C=
super users=E2=80=9D of its inflation data, giving a bit of detail about wh=
y publicly announced inflation data was surprising. At the New York Times, =
Ben Casselman and Jeanna Smialek <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wNC8w=
NS9idXNpbmVzcy9lY29ub215L2xhYm9yLXN0YXRpc3RpY3Mtc3VwZXItdXNlcnMuaHRtbA/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdc2786a4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">have more about the super users</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Bureau of Labor Statistics shared more inf=
ormation about inflation with Wall Street =E2=80=9Csuper users=E2=80=9D tha=
n previously disclosed, emails from the agency show. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Emails obtained through a Freedom of Informati=
on Act request show that the agency =E2=80=94 or at least the economist who=
 sent the original email, a longtime but relatively low-ranking employee =
=E2=80=94 was in regular communication with data users in the finance indus=
try, apparently including analysts at major hedge funds. And they suggest t=
hat there was a list of super users, contrary to the agency=E2=80=99s denia=
ls. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many of the recipients appear to have been in-=
house economists at large investment banks such as Barclays, Nomura and BNP=
 Paribas.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Others work for private research firms, which =
sell their analysis to investors. And some recipients appear to have been a=
nalysts at large hedge funds such as Millennium Capital Partners, Brevan Ho=
ward and Citadel, which trade directly on their research.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The emails were never=C2=A0<em>material</em>, =
exactly. But:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is no evidence in the emails that the em=
ployee provided early access to coming statistical releases or directly sha=
red other data that wasn=E2=80=99t available to the public. In several inst=
ances, the employee told users that he couldn=E2=80=99t provide information=
 they had requested because it would require disclosing nonpublic data.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the emails show that the employee did enga=
ge in extended, one-on-one email exchanges with data users about how the in=
flation figures are put together. Such details, though highly technical, ca=
n be of significant interest to forecasters, who compete to predict inflati=
on figures to hundredths of a percentage point. Those estimates, in turn, a=
re used by investors making bets on the huge batches of securities that are=
 tied to inflation or interest rates.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that there was once a view that sendin=
g hedge funds an=C2=A0inflation data release in advance is obviously bad, b=
ut answering their technical questions after the information is released is=
 fine.=C2=A0The super users were the ones who really cared about the data, =
and helping them understand it better was good customer service and didn=E2=
=80=99t really hurt anyone else. But I=E2=80=99m not sure people think that=
 anymore.</p>
