<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic rule is that neither public nor priv=
ate companies are allowed to lie to their investors to raise money. Securit=
ies fraud is securities fraud, whether you are public or private.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMDYvZG9nZWNvaW4taXMtdXAtYmVjYXVzZS1pdC1zLWZ1bm55P2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDA0MTAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB2f015cef" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">more advanced rule</a> is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0l=
ook, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34992007.2853=
53/aHR0cHM6Ly9zY2hvbGFyc2hpcC5sYXcudXBlbm4uZWR1L2NnaS92aWV3Y29udGVudC5jZ2k_=
YXJ0aWNsZT0zMTU4JmNvbnRleHQ9ZmFjdWx0eV9zY2hvbGFyc2hpcA/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB9b34a3b0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">things are a bit laxer for private companies</a>. (N=
ot legal advice!) A public company is, in some sense, always on the record:=
 If a public-company chief executive officer=C2=A0says something=C2=A0on te=
levision or social media, the stock will move, and if it later turns out to=
 be false then someone will sue. A private company does not have that risk,=
 since its stock doesn=E2=80=99t trade; its main risk of committing fraud i=
s when it raises money directly from investors. If its CEO says something f=
alse on television, the company can clean that up later when it does a fina=
ncing round, sending out an offering memo that says =E2=80=9Cby the way our=
 CEO said some numbers on TV last month, but here are the real numbers.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are other advantages. Private companies =
have fewer shareholders who are generally more loyal and less likely to sue=
, and their disclosures are less likely to fall into the hands of the US Se=
curities and Exchange Commission.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s another one. If you are a publi=
c company in the US, you have to report your financial results under US gen=
erally accepted accounting principles. You are, in some circumstances, allo=
wed to talk about alternative=C2=A0numbers that=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0</em>comply with GAAP, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluL25vbi1nYWF=
wLWZpbmFuY2lhbC1tZWFzdXJlcy5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f0904af" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>the SEC dislikes it</a>, and generally pushes companies to emphasize the G=
AAP numbers rather than the non-GAAP ones, and in any case to reconcile the=
 two. You can=E2=80=99t just go around saying =E2=80=9Cwe are profitable, a=
djusting for certain costs,=E2=80=9D and leave it at that. You have to show=
 your work, and you have to lead with the fact that you are unprofitable.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if you are a private company, you ar=
e not allowed to=C2=A0<em>lie</em>; you are not allowed to present financia=
l information that is=C2=A0<em>misleading.=C2=A0</em>But are you always hel=
d strictly to GAAP? Do your investor presentations have to start with the b=
ad news that you have negative net income, rather than the good news that y=
ou have positive =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMTgtMDQtMjcvd2V3b3JrLWFjY291bnRzLWZvci1jb25zY2lvdXNuZXNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
A0MTAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB2e485b5b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">community-adjusted EBITDA</a>=E2=80=9D or whatever? N=
ah, you are a private company, nobody expects you to be GAAP profitable, yo=
ur sophisticated investors know what information they need, and you can giv=
e them that. You have a bit more leeway to report results according to acco=
unting principles that are acceptable=C2=A0<em>to you</em>, rather than one=
s that are=C2=A0<em>generally=C2=A0</em>accepted.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice this means that many private compa=
nies are =E2=80=9Cprofitable,=E2=80=9D on some bespoke adjusted basis, long=
 before they are profitable as a matter of GAAP net income. Here are Bloomb=
erg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Kiel Porter, Loren Grush, and Edward Ludlow <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMTAvaXMtZWxvbi1tdXNrLXMtc=
3RhcmxpbmstcHJvZml0YWJsZS1zcGFjZXgtc2F0ZWxsaXRlcy1hcmUtbW9uZXktbG9zZXJzP2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDA0MTAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBb51eb601" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">on SpaceX</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SpaceX=E2=80=99s prized Starlink satellite bus=
iness is still burning through more cash than it brings in.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People familiar with the finances of one of th=
e world=E2=80=99s most valuable private companies say Starlink has =E2=80=
=94 at times =E2=80=94 lost hundreds of dollars on each of the millions of =
ground terminals it ships, casting doubt on claims by Chief Executive Offic=
er Elon Musk and the company=E2=80=99s top brass that the business is in =
=E2=80=9Cprofitable territory.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Starlink, which provides space-based internet =
service to more than 2.6 million customers, often strips out the hefty cost=
 of sending its satellites into space to make the non-public numbers look b=
etter to investors, these people said, asking not to be identified discussi=
ng private information. They describe the company=E2=80=99s accounting as =
=E2=80=9Cmore of an art than a science=E2=80=9D and say it=E2=80=99s not ac=
tually profitable based on an operational and ongoing basis.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am always on the lookout for private compani=
es that report customized profitability metrics that make them look=C2=A0<e=
m>less=C2=A0</em>profitable than GAAP would, but I never seem to find any.<=
/p>
