<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic analysis of banking is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A bank owns a pile of assets:=C2=A0lo=
ans, bonds, etc. Say they are worth $100 today.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">The bank is funded mostly by senior claims on those assets: b=
ank deposits and other forms of debt that really should get paid back.=C2=
=A0Say the bank has $90 of debt outstanding against its $100 of assets.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank also has a little sliver of =
equity: its shareholders have the residual claim on those assets, after the=
 senior claims=C2=A0paid back. Here the bank has $10 of equity; depositors =
and other creditors are entitled to the first $90 of the bank=E2=80=99s ass=
ets, but anything left over =E2=80=94=C2=A0currently $10 =E2=80=94=C2=A0goe=
s to the shareholders.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The shareho=
lders, therefore, have a close-to-the-money <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL=
3dpa2kvTWVydG9uX21vZGVs/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5e571990" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>call=
 option=C2=A0</em>on the bank=E2=80=99s assets</a>: If the assets turn out =
to be worth more than $90, the shareholders get the excess, but if they tur=
n out to be worth less than $90, the shareholders get nothing. In particula=
r, if the assets turn out to be worth zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0if all $100 of as=
sets turn out to be fake and the bank is worthless =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the =
shareholders only lose their $10; the other $90 of the losses fall on the d=
epositors. (Or=C2=A0the deposit insurance fund, the taxpayers,=C2=A0etc.)</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This option is more valuable if vol=
atility is higher. If the bank=E2=80=99s assets have a 50/50 chance of endi=
ng up worth $98 or $102, then the shareholders will get back either $8 or $=
12 after paying off the debt, for an expected value of $10. (And the deposi=
tors will always get back their $90.) If the bank=E2=80=99s assets have a 5=
0/50 chance of ending up worth $70 or $130, then the shareholders will get =
back either $0 or $40, for an expected value of $20. And the depositors wil=
l get back $90 in the good case, but only $70 =E2=80=94=C2=A0a catastrophe,=
 a bank failure =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the bad case.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">The bank=E2=80=99s executives have fiduciary duties to shareh=
olders, and probably own a lot of stock themselves, so they want to make th=
e stock more valuable.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Again, the =
theoretically correct way to=C2=A0make the stock more valuable is to make t=
he assets more volatile, to make the bank riskier, to increase the value of=
 the shareholders=E2=80=99 option.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Everything <em>else </em>about banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0bank regulation, prude=
ntial supervision, capital and liquidity requirements, deposit insurance, r=
ules about bonuses and clawbacks, bank culture and training, speeches by po=
liticians, depictions of banks in popular culture =E2=80=94=C2=A0is about m=
itigating this essential problem. The essential problem is that, if you loo=
k at a bank=E2=80=99s capital structure with some financial sophistication =
but also some naivety, you will say =E2=80=9Cwait the bank works for the sh=
areholders, the shareholders have an at-the-money option on the assets, and=
 the way to increase shareholder value is to increase the volatility of tho=
se assets.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many stories about banks are that story, the s=
tory of someone looking at a bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet with financial so=
phistication and also naivety and saying =E2=80=9Chey what about some more =
risk?=E2=80=9D Here=E2=80=99s a great one <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/34992007.285353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
