kground-color: #ccc;">hiring sheep to mow your lawn</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street investors are deploying flocks of =
sheep to trim the grass covering their solar panel installations as they se=
ek to burnish their green credentials and win local support for sometimes d=
ivisive new renewable energy projects. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The number of solar power sites using sheep to=
 graze the grass and pervasive Russian thistle that grow around panels has =
risen 10-fold over the past two years, according to not-for-profit trade bo=
dy the American Solar Grazing Association. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jonathan Kett, executive director of special p=
rojects at DE Shaw Renewable Investments (Desri), said: =E2=80=9CWe typical=
ly sign contracts for what we call vegetation management, which is just a f=
ancy way of saying =E2=80=98cutting the grass and weeds=E2=80=99, and in a =
lot of our portfolios we consider whether sheep are a practical option=E2=
=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89. in some instances it=E2=80=99s a really natural=
 fit.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re not the ones out there =
shepherding the sheep around and getting in water and stuff,=E2=80=9D he ad=
ded.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from George Steer at the Financial Tim=
es, and the whole article is like that, both thought-provoking and soothing=
. How do the hedge funds find the sheep? Oh, mostly wandering farmers:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Solar power companies and farmers =
team up in =E2=80=9Cquite a grassroots kind of way=E2=80=9D, said ASGA pres=
ident Nick Armentrout. =E2=80=9COften it=E2=80=99s as simple as there=E2=80=
=99s a solar site under construction or constructed and a neighbouring farm=
er just stops in there and asks questions.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I spent a great deal of time this morning imag=
ining the hedge fund renewables investor leaning=C2=A0against a fence, surv=
eying the construction site, chewing on a stalk of straw, when a neighborin=
g farmer wanders up to ask questions and strike a sheep-lawn-mowing deal. I=
 think it will be the opening scene of my Cormac McCarthy-influenced financ=
e novel.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The sheep are not just good at mowing the lawn=
, they are also good at maintaining a rural vibe so that neighbors do not o=
bject:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Desri=E2=80=99s executive director of developm=
ent Liz Peyton said that in cases where land had been used for agriculture =
prior to the construction of a solar site, =E2=80=9Cit can be a hard transi=
tion for local communities=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf they know that the land isn=E2=80=
=99t going to be used for a dairy farm, but that sheep will still be grazin=
g, that helps to ease some of the hesitance around the change,=E2=80=9D Pey=
ton added.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand,=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>the =
sheep good at mowing the lawn? There are contrarian views:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe sheep didn=E2=80=99t like to eat =
the weeds we needed them to eat, plus their hair kept getting caught in the=
 inverters, causing equipment damage,=E2=80=9D said a spokesperson for a Fl=
orida-based renewable energy group who asked not to be named.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CConsidering all those factors, they w=
ound up not saving money [compared with] traditional mowing,=E2=80=9D the p=
erson said. =E2=80=9C[The sheep] were super cute, and our customers loved t=
hem, but alas.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right the sheep still need to make financi=
al sense.</p>
